The paper deals with concentration of measure inequalities for randomized Toeplitz matrices, which are commonly used in signal processing and information theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.SP (Signal Processing) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also discusses the application of these inequalities in Compressive Binary Detection (CBD), which falls under the category of machine learning and data analysis. Hence, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is also a likely sub-category. The paper involves mathematical analysis and probabilistic techniques, which are commonly used in numerical analysis and scientific computing. Therefore, cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) is another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the analysis of sparse signals, which is a topic of interest in compressed sensing and sparse recovery. Hence, cs.SI (Signal and Image Processing) is also a possible sub-category.
